      "shortest": true,
      "solution": "n = gets.to_i\n\ndigits = n.digits.size\nexponent = (digits - 1) / 3\nmultiplier = 1e3 ** exponent\nvalue = n / multiplier\n\nputs \"#{\"%g\" % value}k#{exponent}\"",
      "statement": "Scientific notation generally assumes base 10, but it can be used with any base.\n\nAn <<e>> is used to imply 'exponent' where in base 10 this means <<*10^>> (<<times 10 to the power of>>), e.g. {{2e4}} = 2*10^4 = 20000.\n\nHere we use a <<k>> to mean <<*1000^>> (<<times 1000 to the power of>>). Some examples are shown below, showing a number, then showing it represented in base 10 (<<e>>) and base 1000 (<<l>>) scientific notation.\n\n{{1000000000000}}\n<<e>>: {{1e12}}\n<<k>>: {{1k4}}\n\n{{2419300000000}}\n<<e>>: {{2.4193e12}}\n<<k>>: {{2.4193k4}}\n\n{{400}}\n<<e>>: {{4e2}}\n<<k>>: {{400k0}}",
